{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512477"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:55:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:55:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11905"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11905"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.01,0.49,0.38,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4501"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100255"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4501"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11905"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82653"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6742"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38482"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100255"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking advice about weight loss options. She reports struggling with diet and exercise modifications over several years without success. She does not want to consider bariatric surgery due to concerns about the procedure and recovery period. She has a medical history of pancreatitis twice, a non-ST elevation myocardial infarction 12 months ago, and chronic back pain. Her regular medications include aspirin, metoprolol, atorvastatin, and a buprenorphine patch for pain management. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her weight is 82 kg and height is 162 cm, giving a BMI of 31 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would be most suitable for weight management in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Naltrexone-bupropion","Bisacodyl","Semaglutide","Orlistat","Phentermine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has obesity (BMI 31 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E) and is seeking pharmacological management after lifestyle modifications have been unsuccessful. When considering pharmacotherapy for obesity, efficacy, contraindications, and adverse effects must all be carefully considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrlistat\u003C/strong\u003E works by inhibiting pancreatic lipases, reducing fat absorption by approximately 30%. It produces modest weight loss of 2-3% more than diet alone at 12 months. Its main advantage in this patient is its safety profile - it has no cardiovascular concerns, does not interact with her current medications, and is not contraindicated in patients with a history of pancreatitis. While gastrointestinal side effects like oily stools, flatulence, and fecal urgency can limit adherence, it represents the safest effective option for this patient with multiple comorbidities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaltrexone-bupropion\u003C/strong\u003E combination therapy is contraindicated in this patient due to her use of buprenorphine. Naltrexone is an opioid antagonist that would precipitate opioid withdrawal and interfere with pain management. Additionally, bupropion in the combination could potentially interact with her existing medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBisacodyl\u003C/strong\u003E is a stimulant laxative that has no role in weight management. While it may cause temporary weight loss through fluid depletion, it does not reduce body fat and chronic use can lead to electrolyte disturbances and dependency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESemaglutide\u003C/strong\u003E, a GLP-1 receptor agonist, is highly effective for weight loss but is contraindicated in this patient due to her history of pancreatitis. GLP-1 agonists increase the risk of pancreatitis and should be avoided in patients with a history of pancreatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhentermine\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in this patient due to her history of ischaemic heart disease. As a sympathomimetic agent, it can increase blood pressure and heart rate, potentially exacerbating underlying cardiac conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Orlistat is a safe pharmacological option for weight management in patients with cardiovascular disease and pancreatitis.","Semaglutide is contraindicated in patients with a history of pancreatitis.","Naltrexone-bupropion is contraindicated in patients using opioid medications."],"references":["Finkelstein, EA, Verghese, NR. Incremental cost-effectiveness of evidence-based non-surgical weight loss strategies. Clin Obes. 2019; 9:e12294. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1111/cob.12294","MedlinePlus [Internet]. Bethesda (MD): National Library of Medicine (US); [updated 2021 Jun]. Prescription Medications to Treat Overweight \u0026 Obesity; . Available from: Available at: https://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/weight-management/prescription-medications-treat-overweight-obesity#which"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82653"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11905"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82653"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-25T08:36:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-25T08:38:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4501"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100255"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"